they also tested for diabetes which honestly could kind of line up with the symptoms that i was having so i can’t blame them for that. i don’t believe that was weight-based assumption. overall, it was a super positive experience. i’m happy.

although i will say, it was very strange to me that they did a pregnancy test without even asking me (i am very much not active, esp not with… penii? penises? LMAO) but i understand that ppl lie about that sometimes.

i also got an incredibly kind nurse who was heavier than i am (i would say medium fat but i’m not sure if identifying other fat ppl this way is respectful) and she was incredibly understanding of my worries about the tests she was running.

there are a couple contributing factors that make it slightly less lucky in my case, namely that i am a small fat (especially since i have lost weight due to the mystery illness that i went in to the urgent care for) so it’s easier in my case not to assume that it’s weight based.

i am just now realizing how lucky i got with the doctors i saw at urgent care the other day. most of the testing they did, if not all of it, lined up with my actual symptoms and for maybe the first time ever, i was not told to lose weight. at all. they didn’t even weigh me.

ok rant over. just thought i’d document this moment in my life cause it’s been a while since i’ve been able to look at my body in its natural state and smile.

maybe if we removed the values assigned to certain sizes of clothing, every store could carry every size and be inclusive of every size because literally every human on this planet requires clothing that fits them properly. it’s a necessity.

i do have to say though that this veil of shame being down for however long is bringing to the forefront of my brain how much of an accessibility issue buying plus size clothing is. i just need clothes that fit and yet finding them is 5x as difficult than for small ppl.

what is the purpose of staying in too small clothing? just for the purpose of being able to say “well i’m not a size 20, so i’m fine”. if my body is a size 20, then my body is a size 20. there is no inherent value either way to the size that i am.

am i overcoming the fear of being larger sizes that i’ve had for my entire life?? it used to make me want to cry to think about getting bigger clothes bc i was embarrassed, but what is embarrassing about buying clothing that fits you? you have to buy clothing that fits anyway.

like, we are all just the sizes we are. there is and should not be inherent value in one size versus another. i am the size that i am, i am me-sized, and i am beautiful and lovely as a me-sized individual. it doesn’t matter what size clothes are bc they just have to be me-sized.

like… i hope this lasts. i just walked past my mirror, looked at myself in a way that usually makes me uncomfy, and smiled. like, i’m so beautiful. my size is literally just my size. it does not matter and people who think it does are weird as hell.

y’all i literally have been repeating to myself like a mantra that there is nothing wrong with my body, and that the value society has assigned to being a certain size does not affect me if i don’t want it to, and i’m genuinely happy seeing myself in the mirror again.
